    {
      "type": "h1",
      "content": "Introduction to Solutions"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "A <b>solution</b> is a <span class=\"highlight\">homogeneous mixture</span> of two or more components. The component present in larger amount is called <b>solvent</b> and the one in smaller amount is called <b>solute</b>."
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Types of Solutions"
    },
    {
      "type": "h1",
      "content": ""
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Concentration of Solutions"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Different ways to express concentration:"
    },
    {
      "type": "h1",
      "content": ""
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Solubility"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "<b>Solubility</b> is the maximum amount of solute that dissolves in a given amount of solvent at a given temperature."
    },
    {
      "type": "h1",
      "content": ""
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Henry's Law"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Henry’s law states that the solubility of a gas in a liquid is directly proportional to the partial pressure of the gas."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "$p = k_H \\cdot x$"
    },
    {
      "type": "h1",
      "content": "Applications of Henry’s Law"
    },
    {
      "type": "h1",
      "content": ""
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Raoult’s Law"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "The partial vapor pressure of each component is directly proportional to its mole fraction."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "$p_A = p_A^0 \\cdot x_A$"
    },
    {
      "type": "h1",
      "content": "Ideal vs Non-Ideal Solutions"
    },
    {
      "type": "h1",
      "content": ""
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Colligative Properties"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "These properties depend only on number of solute particles, not their nature."
    },
    {
      "type": "h1",
      "content": ""
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Abnormal Molar Mass"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Due to <b>association</b> or <b>dissociation</b> of solute particles, observed molar mass differs."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "content": "Van’t Hoff factor: $i = \\frac{observed\\ value}{normal\\ value}$"
    },
    {
      "type": "h2",
      "content": "Van’t Hoff Factor"
    },
    {
      "type": "h1",
      "content": ""
    },
    {
      "type": "callout",
      "content": "Focus on formulas of colligative properties and Van’t Hoff factor. Numerical questions are very common from this chapter.",
